  "film_direction": "Palette system: warm paper canvas dominates; black ink carries structure and body copy; muted red is reserved for reversals, stamps, active numbers, and the single changing protagonist in a diagram. Secondary colors stay quiet and material-like, never neon.\n\nType roles: display type is used for one large concept per scene; body text is sparse and subordinate; mono text is only for version numbers, counters, and labels that need a measured feeling.\n\nMotion defaults + budget: each scene gets one macro movement plus one or two live secondary elements. Entries use `EASE.entry`; emphasis uses `EASE.emphasis`; ambient motion uses `EASE.drift` only when the scene needs a living hold. Avoid exit tweens before transitions; scenes should reach a readable hero frame and let the harness transition carry the cut.\n\nAmbient system: paper grain, light grid, ink-line frames, small pinned details, and subtle offset shadows recur across the film. The frame should feel like a careful notebook argument, not a startup pitch deck.\n\nNegative list: no real product screenshots, no website capture, no generic AI glow, no purple-blue tech gradients, no dense dashboards, no decorative bokeh, no stock-photo startup imagery.\n\nTransition vocabulary: use `crossfade`, `blur-crossfade`, `push-slide`, and `zoom-through` only. Continue runs keep the same visual stage and evolve the carried object in one worker.\n\nVisual register mix: scenes 1-2 are kinetic metaphor and abstract pressure; scene 3 is timeline/type; scenes 4-5 are process and score transformation; scene 6 is simple data proof; scene 7 is spatial analogy; scenes 8-9 are diagram-to-closing editorial image.\n\nStillness-before-climax allocation: scene 6 holds after the PMF balloon collapses into cashflow; scene 9 holds on the final line.\n\nCaptions: transcript captions occupy the lower band; primary graphics stay above the caption territory unless a scene intentionally gives the caption the final word.",
